Well folks, I've been following c.o.o.a for well-nigh 4 years now, and
have been using OS/2 for just about that long, too. I've had the pleasure
of reading posts (and diatribes) from Mike Timbol, Dave Tholen, Brian
Sturgill, et al, if only for their entertainment value. I also work in
a shop that is very MS oriented, and have a lot of experience with 
Windows, WFW, and NT 3.5 - we're building an NT server as I speak.

SO, I have a good bit of exposure to most all of the operating systems
that have been the focus of much debate in this and other advocacy
groups, and I have come to an irrevocable conclusion.

They are all damn good operating systems. And I enjoy using all of'em.

I like Warp because it's stable, forgiving, and has the best GUI of the
bunch. I even <gasp> like IBM Works, and WebExplorer is A LOT of fun
to use. I'm using HyperAccess Lite right now, and contrary to what I've
read here, it works great with my Practical Peripherals PC144LCD. For
$70US, I think Warp with the Bonus Pak is one of the best software
values on the market today.

I like NT because of its connectivity. We're currently migrating our
Novell apps over to NT and connecting our NT server to our SUN Unix
and mainframe systems, and I've been very impressed with how easy NT
is to work with.

I have no idea why I like Windows. To me, Windows is kind of like a little
sister. She's a pain in the ass, unpredictable as hell, but you love her
anyway. OK, OK, I love my little sister (she's 41 now) and I don't love
Windows, but I don't mind using it every now and then.

SO, who's gonna win in the long run? I don't think it's gonna come down
to who has the best OS. If it did, NextStep would probably win. The
winner is gonna be the guy with the best marketing, and that sure isn't 
going to be IBM. Much as I like Warp, I can understand why Brian Sturgill
and others are developing for NT and W95 instead. MicroSoft has a 
good (not great) product, and has marketed the hell out of it. IBM seems
to think they can still sell their products on their name only, and they
are going to get burned for it. Their old arrogance is still there, and
it hurts'em alot. Microsoft has that same arrogance, but they do a good
job of hiding it behind a marketing structure that HAS to be envied by
everyone in the industry. I've been to quite a few Microsoft education
classes and seminars, and they know how to talk to people. I've been to
IBM seminars and it reminded me of the sock hops I went to in Junior High
in the early 60's.

I like Warp. It has a great GUI, it's stable, it's easy to use, and I'll
be using it for at least another year. But I think IBM's missed the boat,
which is connectivity and marketing. It's too bad, because they have one
hell of a product. It's too bad they don't know what to do with it.

SO, Brian, how do you like Fort Collins? Must have surprised the hell
out of the locals to see an out-of-state license plate that said something
besides "California" :)...
