>It's not taken them this long to *decide* but to *deliver* (without MS code).

I don't believe this for an instant.  IBM wanted to capitalize on it
-- that's why TCP/IP was a separate package that cost more than all of
the rest of OS/2.  How long has that package been available?

IBM could *easily* have provided basic peer-peer networking in the box
more than five years ago.  They did not, even though they were amongst
the earliest vendors to realize that networking would be important
(recall that they put some network awareness into PC-DOS 3.0 circa
1985)!  That was just plain stupid.

So what happened?  Microsoft shipped WfWG and voila, an instant small
workgroup success.  Even better (for Microsoft) is the fact that WfWG
interoperates seamlessly with NT -- so they can leverage their
existing product to sell NT servers.  They are doing so *very*
effectively as we speak.

So IBM's response with Warp is to bundle Internet utilities -- a move
of startling good-sense -- but without LAN connectivity.  That's kind
of like shipping a sports car with doughnut tires on all four wheels.
What were they thinking?

It's nice that Warp LAN Client will be a better package than WfWG, but
it's years too late and it didn't have to be.

