	Why does everyone assume that it will be winner-take-all in the 
OS wars? Windows 95 may very well outsell Warp. It may even sell in the 
first month more than Warp has done all told. So what?
	At a conservative estimate, OS/2 should have 9 million sold 
before Windows 95 comes out. While that is well below the numbers for 
Windows, it's enough for survival. Atari does quite nicely with far fewer 
users. Yet Atari has some admirable products, such as Calamus. And, if 
the past few years are any indication, OS/2 will continue to grow steadily.
	It would be nice to have OS/2 apps easily available in the 
stores, but that's not strictly necessary. And, when I think of how much 
Microsfot survives on hype and how much distorted information floats 
around about OS/2, I'd love to see Windows buried. Realistically, though, 
I'm not going to stay up at night waiting for that to happen.
	Despite all the scare stories about IBM abandoning OS/2, I think 
that the worst case scenario will be the present one, with OS/2 a distant 
second to Windows and applications available if you know where to look. 
If I have to, I can live with that. I use OS/2 for all my serious work, 
and mostly DOS for games, and everything works just fine. 
	

